{{Politics of Ethiopia}}
Ethiopia is administratively divided into regional states and chartered cities, zones, ''woreda'' (districts) and ''kebele'' (wards).

==Regions and chartered cities==
{{stack|[[Image:Ethiopia regions english.png|thumb|400px|The regions and chartered cities of Ethiopia]]}} 
{{Main|Regions of Ethiopia}}

The 9 regional states or ''kililoch'' are based on ethnic territoriality:
*[[Afar Region|Afar]] Capital Semera
*[[Amhara Region|Amhara]] Capital Bahir Dar
*[[Benishangul-Gumuz Region|Benishangul-Gumuz]] Capital Asosa
*[[Gambela Region|Gambela]] Capital
*[[Harari Region|Harari]]  Capital Harar
*[[Oromia Region|Oromia]]  Capital Finfinne/ Addis Ababa
*[[Somali Region|Somali]]  Capital Jijjiga
*[[Southern Nations, Nationalities, and Peoples' Region]] Capital Hawasa
*[[Tigray Region|Tigray]]  Capital Mekele

==Zones==
{{Main|List of zones of Ethiopia}}

The 9 regions are further subdivided into 68 zones.

==Woreda==
{{Main|Districts of Ethiopia}}

Woreda or [[district]]s are smaller subdivisions.

==Kebele==
{{Main|Kebele}}

Kebele are [[municipality|municipalities]]. They are the smallest administrative division.

==Former provinces==
{{Main|Provinces of Ethiopia}}

Between 1942 and 1991, Ethiopia was divided into 13 provinces. Other provinces existed before 1942.

